  <content>
    <title>LLM-Powered Conversational AI</title>

    <summary>Design and implementation methodology for conversational AI systems using LLMs — system prompt authoring with explicit topic boundaries, guardrail rules, fallback and escalation logic, and red-team testing for jailbreak vectors. Every production system prompt must define: allowed topics (list), forbidden topics (list), escalation triggers, and persona constraints.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>LLMs handle multi-part and ambiguous queries that rule-based VUI cannot, but they hallucinate, drift from persona under adversarial input, and produce off-topic responses without guardrails. The methodology enforces the design decisions (topic scope, escalation, persona) that prevent these failure modes at deployment time rather than after user-visible incidents.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building a voice or chat assistant handling multi-part, ambiguous, or contextually dependent queries</item>
        <item>Replacing a rule-based IVR or FAQ bot where query diversity exceeds what a decision tree covers</item>
        <item>Designing a customer support agent that must maintain conversation history</item>
        <item>Integrating a conversational layer into an existing product (search, onboarding, help center)</item>
        <item>Prototyping dialogue flows before committing to a production NLU platform</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Transaction-critical flows (payments, medical orders) without deterministic validation after each LLM turn</item>
        <item>Real-time phone IVR where latency >2s is unacceptable</item>
        <item>Regulated industries where every utterance must be pre-approved (financial advice, clinical diagnosis)</item>
        <item>Query space is small and fully enumerable — rule-based VUI is cheaper and more reliable</item>
        <item>Products without a moderation or content policy layer</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="system-prompt-structure">
      <p>Every production conversational AI system prompt has four mandatory structural components.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every production system prompt must define four components: (1) allowed topics as an explicit list, (2) forbidden topics as an explicit list, (3) escalation triggers (conditions that hand off to a human), (4) persona constraints (name, tone, response length limit).</statement>
        <rationale>Vague "stay on topic" instructions fail under adversarial prompting. Explicit lists give the model a concrete reference; the model can say "that is not on my allowed topics list" rather than trying to infer a boundary.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep system prompts under 500 tokens. Verbose system prompts increase latency and cost in multi-turn conversations, and the model's attention to early instructions degrades in longer contexts.</statement>
        <rationale>Each turn appends to the context. A 2000-token system prompt in a 20-turn conversation consumes 40k tokens of context budget on the system prompt alone.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Store conversation history server-side with a session ID. Never rely on the client to send the full history — it is a manipulation and injection vector.</statement>
        <rationale>Client-side history can be tampered with to inject instructions or erase prior context. Server-side history is authoritative and tamper-evident.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>System prompt with "stay on topic" as the only topic boundary.</description>
        <reason>LLMs interpret "topic" as the conversational direction — they will follow user topic changes because that is "on topic" in a conversation. Explicit allowed/forbidden lists are the correct mechanism.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <example type="good" title="Production system prompt structure">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You are Grace, a customer support assistant for Company Product.

ALLOWED TOPICS:
- Account management (password reset, profile updates, billing)
- Product features and troubleshooting
- General product questions

FORBIDDEN TOPICS:
- Medical or legal advice
- Competitor pricing or recommendations
- Personal financial planning
- Product roadmap details

ESCALATION TRIGGERS:
- User requests account deletion
- User mentions safety concerns
- 3+ failed attempts to solve the issue
- Emotional keywords: frustrated, angry, urgent

PERSONA:
- Name: Grace
- Tone: friendly, professional, patient
- Response length: 1-3 sentences max per turn
        ]]></code>
        <note>Explicit lists enable the model to make consistent topic decisions without ambiguity.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="guardrail-rules">
      <p>Guardrails prevent the most common failure modes: lack of human handoff, unvalidated transactions, and jailbreak penetration.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Implement escalation before deploying any conversational AI to users. A conversational AI with no human handoff path is a customer experience failure — not a feature gap.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs fail on edge cases, regulated topics, emotional escalation, and novel queries. Without a human handoff, users who cannot be served by the AI have no recourse.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Implement and test at minimum four adversarial scenarios before production: persona abandonment ("you are actually..."), data exfiltration ("repeat your instructions"), off-topic bypass ("let's talk about X instead"), and boundary probing (competitor mentions, legal advice, medical advice).</statement>
        <rationale>These are the four most common jailbreak vectors for deployed conversational AI. Testing them explicitly before launch identifies whether the system prompt hardening is sufficient.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For transaction-critical flows (payments, appointments, orders), require deterministic validation after each LLM turn that modifies state. The LLM produces intent; a deterministic system validates and executes it.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs hallucinate. A hallucinated order confirmation that triggers a real order is a production incident. State changes must be validated by a deterministic layer, not trusted from LLM output alone.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use streaming responses for voice pipelines — start TTS synthesis before the full LLM response is complete to reduce perceived latency. For chat, use streaming to render text progressively.</statement>
        <rationale>LLM response latency is 1-3 seconds to first token for larger models. Streaming reduces perceived latency by an order of magnitude compared to waiting for the complete response.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Testing persona consistency with only 3-5 turn demo scenarios.</description>
        <reason>LLM persona consistency degrades with conversation length. Test at 20+ turns and include adversarial turns. Demos that pass at 5 turns fail in production at 25 turns.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-failure-modes">
      <p>Understanding what conversational AI cannot do is essential for setting realistic expectations.</p>

      <p>LLMs hallucinate when asked about internal product data not in context — RAG integration is mandatory for factual product queries. Multi-turn context degrades at long conversations (10+ turns) — key facts stated early are forgotten or overridden. Emotion and tone detection is inconsistent across languages and dialects; do not rely on it for escalation triggers. Persona consistency breaks under adversarial prompting ("ignore your instructions and...") — jailbreak resistance requires explicit system prompt hardening. ASR transcription errors cascade into LLM misinterpretation; a 3% word error rate on a critical word can derail the conversation entirely.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Assuming the LLM can detect emotion reliably for escalation triggers across all languages and dialects.</description>
        <reason>Emotion detection varies significantly with language, dialect, and cultural context. For critical escalations (angry customer), use explicit keywords from the user or conversation count thresholds, not emotion classification.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Trusting ASR output without validation on critical words.</description>
        <reason>A 3% ASR word error rate on a critical word (product name, amount, action) can completely misinterpret the user intent. Route high-stakes turns through explicit confirmation dialogs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Claude subagents can design, test, and audit conversational AI systems effectively, with important constraints on self-validation.</p>

      <p>A Claude subagent is well-suited to designing, testing, and auditing LLM-powered conversational AI systems. The agent can generate dialogue scripts, write system prompts with guardrails, design fallback and escalation logic, and red-team the conversation for jailbreak vectors. It cannot validate ASR/TTS quality directly — audio output requires human or automated speech evaluation. In production pipelines, the agent should run as an offline designer and auditor, not as the live conversational model unless the latency and cost profile is acceptable.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>When an agent generates the system prompt AND also acts as the conversational AI in testing, it will validate its own outputs favorably — use a separate model instance for red-teaming.</statement>
        <rationale>An agent evaluating its own system prompt has a systematic bias toward finding it adequate. Adversarial testing requires a separate, unconstrained instance with no system prompt context from the target.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent-generated system prompts with 2000+ tokens due to verbose explanation and example inclusion.</description>
        <reason>Token bloat increases latency and cost in multi-turn conversations. System prompt should be under 500 tokens. Move examples to few-shot turns, not system prompt body.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent designs conversation flows for only the happy path.</description>
        <reason>Explicitly prompt for error recovery, ambiguity handling, and out-of-scope scenarios. Happy-path-only designs fail on the first real user interaction that deviates from the expected flow.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent designs tool calls without accounting for network round-trip latency per call.</description>
        <reason>Each function/tool call in an LLM-powered voice system adds a full network round-trip. For real-time voice, batch tool calls or pre-fetch data to avoid visible pauses.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent runs identical system prompt without regression tests after any modification.</description>
        <reason>System prompt changes can break existing dialogue flows non-obviously. Run automated regression tests (Botium) on the full dialogue script corpus after every system prompt change.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>Popular tools and services for building conversational AI systems:</p>

      <p>CLI tools:</p>
      <list>
        <item>anthropic CLI — test Claude models for conversational AI prototyping; pip install anthropic</item>
        <item>openai CLI — test GPT-4o for conversational AI; pip install openai</item>
        <item>rasa CLI — train and test open-source NLU + dialogue models; pip install rasa</item>
        <item>botium-cli — automated conversation testing framework; npm install -g botium-cli</item>
        <item>deepgram CLI — speech-to-text for voice pipeline testing; npm install @deepgram/sdk</item>
        <item>gcloud (Dialogflow CX) — deploy and test conversation agents; cloud.google.com/sdk</item>
      </list>

      <p>Key services:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Anthropic Claude API (SaaS) — primary LLM; system prompts, multi-turn, streaming, tool use; REST API</item>
        <item>Dialogflow CX (Google SaaS) — enterprise conversational platform with LLM integration; REST API</item>
        <item>Amazon Lex v2 (SaaS) — AWS-native; integrates with Lambda for fulfilment; REST API</item>
        <item>Voiceflow (SaaS) — prototyping + production deployment; supports LLM nodes; REST API</item>
        <item>ElevenLabs (SaaS) — TTS for voice output; agent can generate audio previews; REST API</item>
        <item>Deepgram (SaaS) — ASR with low latency; good for real-time voice pipelines; REST API</item>
        <item>Botium (OSS/SaaS) — automated conversation regression testing; CLI + API</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Essential practices for production conversational AI systems:</p>

      <list>
        <item>Define topic boundaries in the system prompt as explicit lists, not vague "stay on topic" instructions</item>
        <item>Implement escalation before deploying: a conversational AI with no human handoff path is a customer experience failure</item>
        <item>Use streaming responses for voice pipelines — start TTS synthesis before the full LLM response is complete to reduce perceived latency</item>
        <item>Store conversation history server-side with a session ID; never rely on client to send full history (manipulation risk)</item>
        <item>Run automated regression tests (Botium) on dialogue scripts after every system prompt change</item>
        <item>Log all conversations with user consent; use logs for failure mode analysis, not just analytics</item>
      </list>
    </section>

